In the Mss. reading (cum verus et iustus atque honestus labor) the corruption seems to rest upon cum verus, —cum arising from a misunderstanding of the abbreviation used for quoniam, and verus probably representing an original virtus. The substantives honoribus, praemiis, and splendore suggest a triple distribution of thought in what precedes.

45, 198. qai, struck out by Madvig (after Rubner), bracketed in W2. It seems best, however, to retain it. The main thought is that the Romans have won eminence and distinction by bringing legal knowledge to the service of others; a comparison of the means (auctoritas and inqeniu-m) by which this has been brought about is an incidental matter and properly holds the rank of a subordinate clause.
